<P>
Fluoride, the most widely used treatment for osteoporosis in the world, is not 
effective and increases the risk of fractures in women with the debilitating 
bone disorder, a four-year study released Wednesday said. 
</P>
<P>
The study, published in the New England Journal of Medicine, shows that, 
although fluoride did increase bone mass, the new bone was structurally unsound 
and the treatment actually led to a threefold increase in the number of bone 
fractures. 
</P>
